The former Rivonia Trialist has been remembered fondly by former and current politicians as a man of integrity. JOHANNESBURG - Former finance minister Trevor Manuel says anti-apartheid activist Ahmed Kathrada passed away with his integrity and character intact.Tributes continue to pour for the struggle stalwart who died on Tuesday morning in Johannesburg.The former Robben Island prisoner and Rivonia Trialist has been remembered fondly by former and current politicians as a man of integrity.Manuel paid Kathrada s partner fellow comrade Barbara Hogan a visit to pass his condolences. He left with the same resilience and dignity that he lived with. My personal contact goes back to 1985 when I was detained in solitary and at Pollsmoor prison and he slipped passed my cell, said hello to be me and asked me to be strong on my way to the hospital and the next day he sent me a poem. WATCH: Ahmed Kathrada dies at the age of 87At the same time, African National Congress (ANC) treasurer general Zweli Mkhize has also paid tribute to Kathrada and his lifelong commitment to the struggle for freedom. And the fact that he has worked very well with Nelson Mandela, Walter Sisulu and all the other Rivnia Trialists - it shows you the level of courage that he has had over the years. Mkhize says Kathrada was prepared to do whatever it took during apartheid to ensure South Africa s liberation. Over those years, he was always at the centre of things; where things happened, he was there. He was among among those who worked with our leadership in the establishment of the Freedom Charter. #ripahmedkathrada From meeting political leaders Yasser Arafat & Barack Obama, to attending children's charity events, #ewn takes a look, in pictures, at the life of #strugglestalwart Ahmed #kathrada who passed away this morning. : AFP & EWN.A post shared by Eyewitness News (@ewnupdates) on Mar 27, 2017 at 11:43pm PDT(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)